"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/diffgram/diffgram/labels/security","name":"security","color":"78CFE1","default":false,"description":""},{"id":3537555989,"node_id":"LA_kwDOCM48Rc7S2tIV","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/diffgram/diffgram/labels/developer-experience","name":"developer-experience","color":"EF116A","default":false,"description":""}],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2021-11-10T20:34:57Z","updated_at":"2021-11-10T20:35:52Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"### Purpose\r\nMake it extremely difficult to accidently ship a route that doesn't have a permissions wrapper.\r\n\r\n### Context\r\nAs more people contribute to it, this is something that is easy to get missed, especially for small new endpoints.\r\n\r\n### Idea\r\nAll routes must have a permission wrapper even if that wrapper is no permissions\r\n\r\nWe have some type of a global before all that validates if that exists. And if not it doesn't compile, or something like that.\r\n\r\nMore generally, if some obvious state would cause the application to be in an insecure state it will refuse to compile/start etc\r\n\r\n### Implementation specifics\r\ncan place on the startup check class before starting the server\r\nFor the exceptionally rare cases of completely public endpoints we create a new `@public_permission` wrapper or something.\r\n","closed_by":null,"reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/diffgram/diffgram/issues/434/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/diffgram/diffgram/issues/434/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null}